Introduction¶

The data set analyzed in this projects contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. I will answer the following questions:

  • 2. Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • 3. Which genre is the most profitable one?
  • 4. Who is the most popular actor?
  • 5. Generating a wordcloud from keywords
  • 6. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  • 7. Does sex really sell?

    Data Cleaning¶

    We can see that in the cast, genres and production_companies and the keywords columns, there are multiple values in one cell, seperated by "|". This format is not useful for analysis. In the next steps I will split the dataset into 4 seperate tables:

    • df_cast: Holding information the movie cast
    • df_genre: information about the movie genres
    • df_production: information about the production companies of a certain movie
    • df_keywords: holding all the different keywords of a movie
    • df: holfing all the remaining information

    By doing so, we will "normalize" the dataset and transform it into a "relational database"-like structure. The "id" column will serve as the primary key to identify each movie and combine information across the 5 tables. I will define a fuction called seperate_and_melt() which will use on each of the 4 columns to seperate the data.

    In [159]:
    # defining the fuction
def seperate_and_melt(df, column):
    # create new df with the id in one column and each of the cast/genre/production companies in a seperate column
    df_new = pd.concat([df['id'], column.str.split("|", expand=True)], axis=1)
    # melt this df, so that there is only an 'id'column and a 'cast/genre/company' column
    df_new = pd.melt(df_new, id_vars=['id'], value_name = column.name)
    # drop variable column
    df_new.drop(['variable'], axis=1, inplace=True)
    # drop none rows
    df_new.dropna(inplace=True)
    return df_new
    In [160]:
    # using the function on the 3 columns to get seperate data frames
df_cast = seperate_and_melt(df, df['cast'])
df_genre = seperate_and_melt(df, df['genres'])
df_production = seperate_and_melt(df, df['production_companies'])
df_keywords = seperate_and_melt(df, df['keywords'])
    In [161]:
    # now we can delete these rows from the original df, so it will only hold useful information
df.drop(['cast', 'genres', 'production_companies', 'keywords'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    3. Which genre is the most profitable one for production companies?¶

    Profitability here is defined as the return on the used budget (revenue / budget). Which genre is cheap to produce and brings in a lot of revenue? To find out, we will create a new column called profit_adj

    In [171]:
    # adding profit column
df['profit_adj'] = df['revenue_adj'] / df['budget_adj']
    In [172]:

    This leads to an problem, because there are movies in the database with a budget of 0, and hence the profit is infinite. Therefore we must exlude those movies!

    In [173]:
    # excludig movies witz zero budget, and merging with genre
df_profit = df[df['budget_adj'] > 0].merge(df_genre, on='id')[['original_title', 'genres', 'profit_adj']]
# grouping by genre and calculating the mean profit per genre
df_profit.groupby(['genres'])['profit_adj'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)

    As we can see from the average revenues, the theory "sex sells" does not hold. The average revenue of films with nudity is lower then the average revenue of films without revenue. Of course this is no real statistical analysis. Inorder to so one would need to calculate the correlation between the revenue and the nudity category. Pearsons correlations coefficient is not suitable here.

    Conclusions¶

    Please visit the subsections of the research questions to find the full answers to the proposed questions!

    1. What are the Top-10 rates movies of all time?¶

    The most popular movie is the The Shawshank Redemption, followed by The Godfather and Whiplash on 3rd. See the full list in the subsection.

    2. Which genres are most popular from year to year?¶

    There is a sharp increase in popularity of Adventure and Western movies in the last years. See the full chart in the subsection.

    3. Which genre is the most profitable one?¶

    The "Family" genre.

    4. Who is the most popular actor?¶

    Samuel L. Jackson.

    5. Generating a wordcloud from keywords¶

    See subsection.

    6. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?¶

    We see that the popularity, the budget and the vote_count are positively correlated with the revenue of a movie.

    7. Does sex really sell?¶

    Movies which include nudity have vastly increased over time. However, the average revenues do not seem to indicate that these movies generally make more money. Further statistical analysis could be performed to confirm these findings.
